---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'About — Irrational';
const description =
  'Why Irrational exists: a frontier model already knows the biases; the value is being told no — adversarially, on demand, and inside your other tools.';

// Structured data — mirrors the family (mdshare/bharatlas). The org avatar is used here,
// as the Person image, not as a rendered headshot.
const aboutSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'Person',
      '@id': 'https://www.sathyasankaran.com/#person',
      name: 'Sathya Sankaran',
      url: 'https://www.sathyasankaran.com',
      image: 'https://github.com/urbanmorph.png',
      sameAs: ['https://www.linkedin.com/in/sathyasankaran/', 'https://github.com/urbanmorph'],
      jobTitle: 'Director',
      worksFor: { '@id': 'https://urbanmorph.com/#org' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Organization',
      '@id': 'https://urbanmorph.com/#org',
      name: 'Urban Morph',
      description: 'Consulting firm building tools to solve mobility in cities.',
      url: 'https://urbanmorph.com',
      logo: 'https://github.com/urbanmorph.png',
      founder: { '@id': 'https://www.sathyasankaran.com/#person' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'SoftwareApplication',
      '@id': 'https://irrational.pages.dev/#app',
      name: 'Irrational',
      url: 'https://irrational.pages.dev',
      applicationCategory: 'EducationalApplication',
      operatingSystem: 'Any',
      offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
      creator: { '@id': 'https://www.sathyasankaran.com/#person' },
      license: 'https://github.com/urbanmorph/irrational/blob/main/LICENSE',
      codeRepository: 'https://github.com/urbanmorph/irrational',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'AboutPage',
      url: 'https://irrational.pages.dev/about',
      name: title,
      description: description,
      mainEntity: { '@id': 'https://irrational.pages.dev/#app' },
      author: { '@id': 'https://www.sathyasankaran.com/#person' },
    },
  ],
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(aboutSchema)} />

  <section class="page-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="label">About</p>
      <h1>An engine for telling you no.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The web is full of bias <em>encyclopaedias</em> you browse and a few <em>practices</em> you'd have to
        remember to do. Almost nothing takes the decision you're actually facing and adversarially audits it.
        That's the gap Irrational fills.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap prose">
    <h2>Why not just ask an LLM?</h2>
    <p>
      A frontier model already knows the 188 biases better than any catalogue. So the value isn't
      <em>informational</em> — it's behavioural. A plain LLM in conversation is trained to agree and help you
      execute your framing; it rarely, unprompted, tells you you're rationalising. Irrational's engine has a
      <strong>fixed adversarial contract</strong> — assume you're biased, refuse to validate, argue the other
      side — that doesn't drift back to helpfulness. And because it's a tool, it can be invoked
      <strong>systematically</strong> (an agent auditing its own draft) rather than only when you remember to.
    </p>
    <p>
      The evidence backs the stance: research finds current LLMs "passively confirm rather than challenge,
      reinforcing cognitive bias," and that adversarial questioning is the single most effective debiasing
      intervention.
    </p>

    <h2>Why I built this</h2>
    <p>
      I'm <a href="https://www.sathyasankaran.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sathya</a>, a director at
      <a href="https://www.urbanmorph.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Urban Morph</a>, where we build tools to
      solve mobility in cities. I kept noticing the same thing: people stop thinking critically the moment an LLM
      hands them a decision.
    </p>
    <p>
      The behavioural biases that should catch those mistakes mostly live in books — they're not cognitively
      convenient, and most of us don't even know <em>where</em> or <em>when</em> to apply them. So instead of
      writing one more thing to read, I put the check in the place those self-reinforcing biases are now most
      prevalent: <strong>inside the LLM tools themselves</strong> — where the decisions are increasingly made, and
      where an agreeable model is least likely to push back.
    </p>

    <h2>The canon</h2>
    <p>
      Every entry is grounded in the foundational work: Kahneman &amp; Tversky's heuristics-and-biases programme
      and prospect theory (<em>Thinking, Fast and Slow</em>); Thaler &amp; Sunstein on choice architecture
      (<em>Nudge</em>); Dan Ariely (<em>Predictably Irrational</em> — this project's namesake); and Cialdini on
      influence. Every claim is cited on the <a href="/sources">sources</a> page.
    </p>

    <h2>The shape</h2>
    <p>
      Irrational runs <strong>no AI model</strong>. It provides the curated adversarial framework, the
      <a href="/biases">22-bias catalogue</a>, and a stateless scaffold — delivered as a public field guide and an
      open <a href="/mcp">MCP</a> tool — and the reasoning is done by whatever model you or your agent already
      have. No API keys. No stored decisions. Nothing leaves you. That's the <a href="/privacy">privacy</a>
      story, and the moat: open, composable, and private in a way a closed SaaS can't be.
    </p>
    <p>
      Open-source — <a href="https://github.com/urbanmorph/irrational" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
        >fork it on GitHub</a
      >.
    </p>

    <p class="disclaimer">
      <strong>Disclaimer.</strong> Irrational is a thinking aid, not professional advice. It is adversarial by design,
      can be wrong, and does not replace legal, financial, medical, or other expert counsel. The audit is produced by
      <em>your</em> own AI, whose output is your responsibility — for high-stakes decisions, verify with a qualified
      professional before you act.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .disclaimer {
    margin-top: 30px;
    padding-top: 18px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--color-taupe);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .disclaimer strong {
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
</style>
